\section*{Infinite sample spaces}

\begin{example}
Toss a coin until the first time it comes up heads.
$$
\Omega = \{1,2,3, \dots\}\ .
$$

So,  $m(n) = 1/2^n$.  Hopefully:
$$
\sum_{\omega} m(\omega) = \frac12 + \frac14 + \frac18 + \cdots = 1\ .
$$
Why? Geometric series.  

$$
1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots = \frac1{1-r}\ ,
$$
If you memorize it, you have to remimber whether it is $r/(1-r)$ or
$1/(1-r)$.  So, lets derive it instead:

\begin{eqnarray*}
S & equiv & 1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots \\
S & = & 1 + r(1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + \cdots) \\
S & = & 1 + rS \\
S(1-r) & = & 1 \\
S& = & 1/(1-r)
\end{eqnarray*}

So works for 1/2.

Math geek question:  Why isn't my proof a happy proof?  Works even if
$r = -1$.  So, ``$1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots = 1/2$''.  Huh?



\end{example}


